raw_data.title: Consultant
raw_data.description: Consultant services involve the provision of principal engineers, process experts, and senior systems engineers to provide system analyses, process studies, and design recommendations.  The Consultant serves as a subject matter expert in these and other highly specialized subject areas such as satellite telecommunications, system design, and engineering.  The Consultant provides technical or specialized guidance in the subject matter field, performs analyses and studies, and presents findings and recommendations to clients.

raw_data.title: IA Engineer Level 1
raw_data.description: Information Assurance Engineer Level 1 services include Certification and Accreditation work, documentation, ensuring IAVA compliance, policy development, and other related tasks.

raw_data.title: IA Engineer Level 2
raw_data.description: Information Assurance Engineer Level 2 services include advanced IA engineering and security design through the evaluation, creation and monitoring of security architecture and design models.   Information Assurance Engineers run SRR’s on the equipment and assist in mitigating any open vulnerabilities.

raw_data.title: IA Engineer Level 3
raw_data.description: Information Assurance Engineer Level 3 services include implementation of security architecture and design models. Information Assurance Engineers lead, monitor, and develop the team to ensure appropriate remedial actions are taken to mitigate open vulnerabilities and prevent future occurrences.

raw_data.title: IP Engineer - Level 1
raw_data.description: Internet Protocol (IP) Engineer Level 1 services include commissioning of complex systems utilizing multiple technologies and troubleshooting of complex intermittent problems.  The IP Engineer 1 is responsible for the design, testing, deployment, and technical support of network services and platforms. Other duties include the management of vendor interfaces for product evaluation and testing, installation standards, acceptance testing, and trouble resolution. The IP Engineer 1 assists in the introduction of new equipment, including documentation of design, operations and management of the equipment, and associated services. The IP Engineer 1 is involved in ongoing support of the IP network and related equipment (routers, switches, firewalls, network interfaces, etc) as well as transport media (MPLS, SONET, ATM, Frame Relay, etc), IP routing, interface configurations, maintenance support, and real-time incident identification and resolution.

raw_data.title: IT Engineer - Level 1
raw_data.description: IT Engineer Level 1 logs and tracks calls using help desk software and maintain history records and related problem documentation, supports provisioning efforts by specifying and procuring new equipment or reutilizing existing equipment, MS Exchange provisioning, VOIP phone configuration, application installation and data transfer between systems. Asset tracking and management responsibilities include updating vendor inventory website, inputting asset information into Remedy and asset lifecycle refreshes. IT Engineer Level 1 performs email administration through monitoring mailbox size utilization, reporting on utilization, and archiving common mailboxes. Also provides level 1 troubleshooting and coordination of support.

raw_data.title: IT Engineer - Level 2
raw_data.description: IT Engineer Level 2 provides a full range of IT systems, network and end-user support for internal staff and in direct support of customer engagements.  Duties include configuration and management of laptops, desktops, servers and LAN equipment, monitoring and support of the IT network, perform installations/configuration, asset tracking and management, email administration, printer maintenance/management, projector maintenance, VOIP phone configuration and management.

raw_data.title: IT Engineer - Level 3
raw_data.description: IT Engineer Level 3 manages the team responsible for the delivery of in-house developed applications, systems integration, database development/administration/management and COTS products selection and implementation.  A significant component of the IT Engineer Level 3 is to serve as the product manager, establishing a product roadmap and delivering regularly scheduled releases according to the plan.  Additional responsibilities include management of application and data architecture, design, development, and engineering as well as having escalated support responsibility for applications.

raw_data.title: Network Operations Level 1
raw_data.description: Network Operations Level 1 ensures networks, products and services meet stringent availability and security integrity targets through direct and proactive monitoring of the Network Operations Security Center’s (NOSC) applications.  This encompasses device commissioning and activations, network monitoring, fault detection, isolation, resolution, central problem escalation, and problem tracking and reporting for all facets of IP and RF satellite hardware and services (data, voice, and video) within the network architecture and infrastructure as well as customer remote sites.

raw_data.title: Network Operations Level 2
raw_data.description: Network Operations Level 2 ensures network and product, availability and integrity through supervising the Network Operations Security Center’s daily operation and personnel. This encompasses device commissioning and activations, network monitoring, fault detection, isolation, resolution, central problem dissemination, and problem tracking, for all facets of IP, VoIP, and RF satellite hardware and services (data, voice, and video) within the overall network architecture and infrastructure as well as remotes.

raw_data.title: Network Operations Level 3
raw_data.description: Network Operations Level 3 is responsible for the service assurance, service delivery, availability, and the integrity of networks and products through leadership and management of the operation of the NOSC and its personnel. This encompasses device commissioning and activations, network monitoring, fault detection, isolation, resolution, central problem escalation, and problem tracking and reporting, for all facets of IP, VoIP, and RF satellite hardware and services (data, voice, and video) within the network architecture and infrastructure as well as customer remote sites. Network Operations Level 3 will design, implement and enforce operating methods and procedures to improve NOSC operating quality of service and increase team efficiency by maximizing, personnel, network management systems and administration tools.

raw_data.title: Program Manager 1
raw_data.description: Program management services involve the identification, analysis, coordination, and mitigation of program risks, creation of schedules and tracking progress, coordinating customer interactions, managing the project within budget constraints.  The Program Manager (PM) performs day-to-day management of overall contract support operations, involving multiple projects and groups of personnel.  The Program Manager serves as the primary interface with Government program personnel on program related issues.  The PM manages acquisition and employment of program resources and organizes, directs, and coordinates planning and production of all contract support activities.  The Program Manager is responsible for developing and enforcing work standards and schedules, and managing financial and administrative aspects of the program with respect to contract requirements.

raw_data.title: Program Manager 2
raw_data.description: The Program Manager 2 owns the customer relationship for designated programs and provides expert support to end users, contracting officers, employing a high degree of customer service.  The Program Manager 2 fulfills new product and service orders for existing programs and new customers, uses various project management techniques including setting initial expectations, timelines, and milestones.  The Program Manager 2 accurately gauges project resource dependencies and works with customers and peers to ensure minimal resource conflicts, constantly reviewing project tasks, and communicating status and impact of changes to customers and stakeholders.  The Program Manager 2 maintains expert knowledge of, and complies with, contracts, Reseller Agreements, terms and conditions, SLAs, and policies and procedures governing the installation and use of products and services.  The Program Manager 2 provides long-term customer support and account management and frequently interaction with customers.

raw_data.title: Program Manager 3
raw_data.description: The primary functions of the Program Manager 3 include project and program management, client management, team leadership and development, and business development. By creating an empowering and non-hierarchical environment, the Program Manager 3 leads large multi-disciplinary teams to deliver complex solutions that achieve expected business results. The Program Manager 3 role typically consists of leading multi-project teams in delivering integrated client solutions and managing client relationships at the executive level while providing direction and oversight to the Program Manager(s) on an engagement. Leadership and expertise in strategy development, global program management and engineering management.

raw_data.title: RF Engineer - Level 1
raw_data.description: Radio Frequency Engineer Level 1 services include commissioning of complex systems utilizing multiple technologies and troubleshooting of complex intermittent problems.  The Radio Frequency Engineer 1 is responsible for the analysis, design, implementation, optimization and enhancement of wireless telecommunications networks. Responsibilities include link budget analyses, system dimensioning for coverage and capacity including traffic analysis, initial system design and dimensioning, coverage planning, site identification, evaluation and zoning support, frequency planning, interference analysis, and optimization.

raw_data.title: RF Engineer - Level 2
raw_data.description: Radio Frequency Engineer Level 2 services include design, application, or system analysis required when modifying or advising corrective solutions with respect to new or existing equipment or systems.  The Radio Frequency Engineer 2 is responsible for advanced analysis, design, implementation, optimization and enhancement of wireless telecommunications networks. Responsibilities include advanced link budget analyses, system engineering for coverage and capacity including traffic analysis, initial system design, coverage planning, site identification, evaluation and zoning support, frequency planning, interference analysis, and optimization.

raw_data.title: RF Engineer - Level 3

Responsibilities include advanced link budgets analysis, system engineering for coverage, and capacity including traffic analysis, initial system design, coverage planning, site identification, evaluation and zoning support, frequency planning , interference analysis, and optimization.

raw_data.title: Systems Engineer - 1
raw_data.description: Systems Engineer Level 1 develops and manages complex, end-to-end network design and integration, coordinating closely with Core Engineering, Solutions Engineering and Program Management. Provide technical analysis and detailed network design including network diagrams, as-built documentation, network resource planning, and associated hardware and software connectivity requirements. Independently create written content that clearly describes a technical solution in document and presentation form.

raw_data.title: Systems Engineer - 2
raw_data.description: Systems Engineer Level 2 develops and manages complex, end-to-end network design and integration, coordinating closely with Core Engineering, Solutions Engineering and Program Management. Provide technical analysis and detailed network design including network diagrams, as-built documentation, network resource planning, and associated hardware and software connectivity requirements.  Independently create written content that clearly describes a technical solution in document and presentation form. Additionally, Systems Engineer Level 2 designs, plans, executes network laboratory and demonstration exercises for existing and potential customers, and provide direct support to Solutions Engineering on advanced systems design and strategic RFP development. Systems Engineer Level 2 supports planning, testing, documentation, and delivery of new product offerings.

raw_data.title: Systems Engineer - 3
raw_data.description: Systems Engineer Level 3 is responsible for requirements definition, design, development, technical project management, systems implementation, and systems documentation. Product Development and Engineering interacts with Core (RF & IP) Engineering, Solutions Engineering, and Program Management to ensure proposed solutions are in concert with current capabilities and our network rollout plans. Systems Engineer Level 3 has intimate knowledge and demonstrated technical expertise in satellite and systems engineering with the ability to communicate and document our technical strategy to external parties through proposals, as-built documentation, product status updates, and presentations.
